          "title": "Sale documents (shtarei mekach) requiring blanks for buyer, seller, amount, field location, and date",
          "display_title": "Sale Documents",
          "timestamp": "02:35"
        },
        {
          "title": "The takanah (rabbinic ordinance) underlying the requirement to leave blanks",
          "display_title": "Takanah Principle",
          "timestamp": "03:01"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Tannaitic Dispute: Three Positions on Pre-writing Documents",
      "display_title": "Three Positions",
      "timestamp": "04:10",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Tanna Kamma: may write boilerplate of all documents, must leave blanks for essentials",
          "display_title": "Tanna Kamma",
          "timestamp": "04:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehuda: forbids writing even the boilerplate of any document",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yehuda Position",
          "timestamp": "04:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Eliezer: strict with get (no boilerplate), lenient with other documents (may write completely)",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Eliezer",
          "timestamp": "04:27"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tosafot's reading of Rabbi Eliezer as both strict and lenient in different contexts",
          "display_title": "Tosafot Reading",
          "timestamp": "05:40"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Gemara: Resolving the Mishnah within Rabbi Eliezer's Framework of Lishmah",
      "display_title": "Gemara Resolution",
      "timestamp": "09:30",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Yehuda amar Shmuel: the Mishnah requires leaving blank the punchline 'Harei at Muteret le-chol Adam'",
          "display_title": "Harei at Muteret",
          "timestamp": "09:30"
        },
        {
          "title": "The essential part of get (toref) must be written lishmah, not just the names",
          "display_title": "Toref Requirement",
          "timestamp": "10:47"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara attributes Mishnah to Rabbi Eliezer's view that the essence of get requires lishmah writing",
          "display_title": "Gemara Attribution",
          "timestamp": "11:57"
        },
        {
          "title": "Three cases (mechubar, all can write, hakosev tofsei gittin) re-interpreted as Rabbi Eliezer",
          "display_title": "Three Cases",
          "timestamp": "13:38"
        },
        {
          "title": "Why all three cases were necessary to establish Rabbi Eliezer's view consistently",
          "display_title": "Why Three Cases",
          "timestamp": "14:02"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Rationale (Takanah) for Leaving Blanks: Three Explanations",
      "display_title": "Three Takanos",
      "timestamp": "22:20",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Tosafot on historical practice: Rabbeinu Tam instituted 'Harei at Muteret' language in gets",
          "display_title": "Rabbeinu Tam Practice",
          "timestamp": "22:20"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Yonatan: takanat sofrim—to ease the burden on scribes preparing documents",
          "display_title": "Takanat Sofrim",
          "timestamp": "25:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Shabtai quoting Chizkiya: takanat ketata—prevent quarrels between husband and wife",
          "display_title": "Takanat Ketata",
          "timestamp": "32:06"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Chisda quoting Avimi: takanat agunot—prevent hasty divorces when get is pre-written",
          "display_title": "Takanat Agunot",
          "timestamp": "34:23"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara discussion: takanat agunot applied to Rabbi Meir and Rabbi Eliezer frameworks",
          "display_title": "Agunot Application",
          "timestamp": "34:38"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Dating of Documents: Why Pre-dating is Prohibited",
      "display_title": "Pre-dating Problems",
      "timestamp": "41:01",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Case of arusa: writing get for betrothed woman before nisuin (marriage)",
          "display_title": "Get for Arusa",
          "timestamp": "41:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ulla's teaching: concern about protecting children's reputation (takanas valad)",
          "display_title": "Takanas Valad",
          "timestamp": "46:04"
        },
        {
          "title": "Concern that pre-dated get will make children appear born out of wedlock",
          "display_title": "Reputation Concern",
          "timestamp": "47:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara resolve: concern applies even to arusa to protect against later-than-expected use",
          "display_title": "Arusa Protection",
          "timestamp": "48:05"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Ruling (Halacha) and Application to Other Shrot (Documents)",
      "display_title": "Halacha Ruling",
      "timestamp": "49:30",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Halacha rules like Rabbi Elazar: require lishmah writing and eidei mesirah, no boilerplate for get",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Elazar Ruling",
          "timestamp": "49:30"
        },
        {
          "title": "Question: do we rule like Rabbi Elazar (strictly) also for other documents?",
          "display_title": "Other Documents",
          "timestamp": "52:34"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Pappa quoting Rava: documents are not pre-written before facts are true (mechezi k'shikra concern)",
          "display_title": "Mechezi k'Shikra",
          "timestamp": "52:46"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara resolves: by non-get documents, writing ahead of time before signing is permissible",
          "display_title": "Non-Get Leniency",
          "timestamp": "54:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "Leniency: can pre-write all terms of loan, sale, or ketubah as long as not signed yet",
          "display_title": "Pre-writing Leniency",
          "timestamp": "54:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "Example: ketubahs are written with all terms before the kinyan is performed",
          "display_title": "Ketubah Practice",
          "timestamp": "56:51"
        }
      ]
    }
